data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class and better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — on failure reports *"Expected: 3, Actual: 5"* vs `IsTrue` which just says *"Expected: True, Actual: False"*
- **`CollectionAssert`** — provides `AllItemsAreNotNull`, `Contains`, `AreEquivalent` (same items, any order), `IsSubsetOf`, etc.
- **Message parameters** — always add a message to `IsTrue`/`IsFalse` calls so failures are diagnosable

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**

```csharp
// Same elements regardless of order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// Exact order matters
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Type checking
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreInstancesOfType(users, typeof(User));

// Uniqueness
CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreUnique(users);
```

> **Note:** `CollectionAssert` works on `ICollection`. If you have `IEnumerable`, call `.ToList()` first.
